@node INTRO "Introduction"

ClockFreq is a little program to measure the clock frequency of your Amiga.
This frequency is different in most models, a standard PAL Amiga2000 has
a clock with a frequency of about 7.09MHz, a standard 4000/040  works with
25MHz. ClockFreq will not give the exact results but approximations, so
trust the printing on your oscillator and not this program. Also, there are
some situations where ClockFreq will completely fail. More in the next
chapters.


@endnode


@node SYSTEM "System requirements"
Your Amiga should fulfil the following technical requirements:

 - AmigaOS 2.0 or better

 - A CIA, this is a chip with is available in all "original" Amigas. Some
   clones may have it or not.


@endnode



@node INSTALLATION "Usage"
Start ClockFreq from the Shell/CLI. ClockFreq will disable the interrupts for
a short moment, so you might better not use it in a very sensitive environment
or while online.
After a short delay ClockFreq will present the following output:
@{B}ClockFreq 1.0@{UB}
020|030 mode
CPU:           25.00060 MHz
Ticks:       54479
Ticks/s:    709379

The first line shows the cpu-mode ClockFreq is running in. If you have a
68020 or 68030, then the first line should be equal to that one above.
Other modes are: 000/010, 040, 060.
The second line shows the measured clock frequency of your amiga. This should
be as close as 1% in most cases to the real clock frequency of you amiga (but
see below). ClockFreq will give more digits then it is able to measure
correctly, in general the digits before the decimal point will be correct, on
some systems you can round to the next two digits after the decimal point
for a correct result.
The third line gives the tick-time ClockFreq has run. This is one way of
calculating the potential error in the result.
The fourth line give you the number of ticks per second. This should be
709379 on real PAL Amigas and 715909 for real NTSC amigas. This is also
a help to check the result of ClockFreq on some Amigas. The result should be
10 times as high on an unexpanded A1000, A500(+), A600, A2000, or 20 times
as high on an A1200. Some accelerator boards will also run at a 20 or 40
times higher frequency. Example: A PAL2000 will have a Tick/s of 709379
and runs at 7.09379MHz.


There are several things that influence the reliability of ClockFreq.

68000/68010: ClockFreq will only give good results if the program is in
real FastRam. If you have only ChipRam, then try to make the DMA-usage
as small as possible, lower the number of colours to 4 or less on a
hires-screen. But you will even then only get about 7.06MHz instead of
7.09 on a PAL Amiga. Having more than 4 colours will give useless results.
I have NO IDEA what happens on a 14/16/28MHz-68000. Send me the result
of ClockFreq, if you have such a beast, please

68020+: You must enable the cache(s) to get a good result. ClockFreq
is unable to compensate waitstates or things like that.

68040: The result is worse than on most other 32bit-machines. If you know
the reason, write me.

68060: Make sure that the first line of the result says "060 mode", or
the result will be useless. The detection of an 68060 depends on an
ExecBase-bit, which might not be 100%-official right now. Some
accelerators set it, maybe some other will not do so. If you have
problems with that, then write me a short mail with the name/type
of your accelerator.


Do not try to disable caches and measure ChipRam performance or something
like that with ClockFreq. This will give misleading results on most machines.

@endnode

@node ORGANISM "Internals of ClockFreq"
The source code is included. Feel free to improve it or use it in your own
progams, if you want to. Maybe you can sent me a short email (not required).

ClockFreq tries to measure how long it takes to run through a loop with 40
NOPs. I have chosen NOP, because it is seldom used in other programs, so
there should be enough left of them even in older Amigas. Another reason is,
that a NOP synchronizes the pipelines (that is what I have been told...) and
so is it easy to measure even on an 060.
In a second loop I try to catch the overhead (DBFs, procedure calls,
start/stop timer calls). Nearly all involved code is put into the caches
before the actual measurement begins, so watch out if you translate the
program to another HLL, do not let the code grow too big.
Interrupts must be diabled or the result will get worse. This also
forbids using of the ReadEClock procedure, which I used in a first version.
Now a CIA is programmed directly, because the vblank timer has a resolution
which is far too low to be useful in this case.

@endnode


